Phase 1 — Identity foundations
Service: identity-service · PostgreSQL `identity` db

Why first: every other phase needs an authenticate account to act as —
order-service calls identity-service.GetUser before it will accept a
checkout (ORD-001), and Kong rejects any protected request before it
reaches a service at all if the JWT doesn't verify. Nothing else in the
system can be meaningfully tested without this phase existing first.

Scenarios covered (Archive/Development/Backend/Scenarios): 1, 2, 3, 10.

Conventions used from here on, in every phase file:
- JSON bodies are camelCase (Jackson default on Spring Boot).
- IDs are UUID strings. (Generation Strategy)
- Timestamps are ISO-8601 UTC.
- Money is a decimal string ("89.99"), never a JSON number — avoids
  implying binary-float precision, matches NUMERIC/Decimal128 in the DB.
- Error bodies are a flat envelope: {"error":{"code":"...","message":"..."}}.
  The `code` is a stable machine-readable string; rule IDs in this doc are
  for traceability only and are never in the actual payload.
- Authorization: Bearer <jwt> is shown as the client would send it. Per
  ARCHITECTURE.md §7, Kong's JWT plugin verifies the signature/expiry
  before the request ever reaches the service — identity-service only
  issues the token (login) and everyone else just trusts Kong's forwarded
  claims. Endpoints marked (admin only) mean Kong (or, until Kong's policy
  is wired up, the service itself as a stopgap) rejects the caller unless
  the forwarded role claim is ADMIN — the `roles.code` value actually
  seeded by the database (Archive/Development/Database §1.1: "INSERT INTO
  roles (id, code) VALUES (1, 'ADMIN'), (2, 'CUSTOMER')"), not the
  business-rules prose term "Administrator."

